  <section xml:id="sec-1-3">
    <title>Book section 1.4: Least Upper Bound axiom</title>
    <paragraphs xml:id="sec-1-3-reading">
      <title>Reading</title>
      <p>
        The least upper bound axiom is what makes the real numbers so special. Pay particular attention to this section.
        <ul>
          <li>definition 1.4.1</li>
          <li>exercise 1.4.2</li>
          <li>exercise 1.4.3</li>
          <li>theorem 1.4.4</li>
          <li>Axiom III (question: Why does the set need to be non-empty? What would be the "least upper bound" of the empty set?)</li>
          <li>theorem 1.4.5</li>
          <li>theorem 1.4.6</li>
          <li>theorem 1.4.7</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        Optional: The first two results establish that square roots (and irrational numbers) exist. The others establish that the real numbers are "uncountable". Both really cool results, but time is limited.
